h limitations, foregrounding the richness of hagiography as a genre integrally resistant to limiting binaristic categories, including rigid gender binaries. The collection showcases scholarship by emerging trans and genderqueer authors, as well as the work of established researchers. Working at the vanguard of historical trans studies, these scholars demonstrate the vital and vitally political nature of their work as medievalists. This volume enables the re-creation of a lineage linking modern trans and genderqueer individuals to their medieval ancestors, providing models of queer identity where much scholarship has insisted there were none, and re-establishing the place of non-normative gender in history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aChristian hagiographyxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aChristian saints in literature. 0aChristian saintszEuropeyTo 1500. 0aGender identityzEuropexReligious aspectsxChristianityxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aGender nonconformityzEuropexReligious aspectsxChristianityxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aSexual orientationzEuropexReligious aspectsxChristianityxHistoryyTo 1500. 4aCentral Middle Ages. 4aGender Studies. 4aHigh Middle Ages. 4aHistory. 4aSociology and Social History. 4aTheology and Religion. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aHagiography, gender, religion, transgender, queer theory.1 aBychowski, M. W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColwill, Lee, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDijk, Mathilde van, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElphick, Kevin C. A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGutt, Blake, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGutt, Blake, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1